Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            note.ViewModel.DraftText =
                Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Why `OnStopped`?** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded (not visible). |
| **Why also `OnDestroying`?** | On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`. |
| **Why not `OnDeactivated`?** | That fires for dialogs/split-screen — the app may never actually background. |
| **Why `Preferences`?** | It's fast and synchronous. Lifecycle handlers must complete quickly (~1–2 s) to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS. |
| **`OnResumed` vs first launch** | `Resumed` does **not** fire on initial launch (sequence is `Created` → `Activated`). Load your initial draft in the page/viewmodel constructor instead. |

This keeps your save/restore logic centralized, works across all platforms, and avoids the common pitfalls.
